SIMPLE: piracy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Piracy
<hw>Pi"ra*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Piracies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. LL.
<ets>piratia</ets>, Gr. <?/. See <er>Pirate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act or crime of a pirate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Common Law)</fld> <def>Robbery on the high seas;
the taking of property from others on the open sea by open violence;
without lawful authority, and with intent to steal; -- a crime answering
to <xex>robbery</xex> on land.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- air piracy -- to commandeer or hijack an airplane -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ By statute law several other offenses committed on the
seas (as trading with known pirates, or engaging in the slave trade)
have been made <xex>piracy</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def></def>⟦ldquo⟧Sometimes used, in a quasi-figurative
sense, of violation of copyright; but for this, <xex>infringement</xex>
is the correct and preferable term.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piragua</ent>⟦br⟧
